2 Market Analysis (Excluding Pharmaceuticals)

2.1 ABC Classification Analysis

2.1.1 What is ABC Analysis?

ABC analysis is an inventory categorization technique that classifies items based on their consumption value. This helps prioritize management efforts:

  • Class A (High Priority): Items representing approximately 80% of consumption volume but only 20% of total items. These require tight control, accurate forecasting, and secure supplier relationships.
  • Class B (Medium Priority): Items representing approximately 15% of consumption volume and 30% of items. These require moderate control with periodic reviews and standard ordering procedures.
  • Class C (Low Priority): Items representing only 5% of consumption volume but 50% of total items. These can be managed with simple controls, bulk ordering, or just-in-time delivery.
Benefits:
  • 💰 Cost Savings: Reduced inventory holding costs
  • 📈 Improved Service: Better availability of critical items
  • ⚡ Efficient Operations: Different management strategies for different item classes

2.2 ABC Analysis Summary & Strategic Implications

🎯 ABC Analysis Key Findings (Non-Pharma)

  • Class A items: Represent 79.6% of total non-pharmaceutical consumption volume from just 3.7% of unique non-pharmaceutical items.
  • Top Item: The single highest volume non-pharmaceutical item, EXAMINATION GLOVES, accounts for 81,393 units (26.77% of total non-pharma volume).
  • Focus Area: Concentrating efforts on Class A non-pharmaceutical items offers the highest return on investment for inventory management and supplier negotiation.
Operational Recommendations:
  • Class A: Daily monitoring, safety stock, multiple suppliers, premium service
  • Class B: Weekly reviews, standard inventory policies, regular supplier relationships
  • Class C: Monthly/quarterly reviews, bulk ordering, consider dropshipping
